<section xml:id="sec-set_op" xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude">
  <title>Operations on Sets</title>


  <introduction>
    <p>
      <ol marker ="I.">
        <li>
          <p>
            <term>Union of Sets: </term> 
            Let <m>A =\{2, 4, 6, 8\} </m> and <m>B=\{6, 8, 10, 12 \}</m> be two arbitrary sets, then union of <m>A</m> and <m>B</m> is written as 
            <me>
              A \cup B.
            </me>
            Where  <me>
              A \cup B = \{2, 4, 6, 8, 10, 12\}
            </me>
            Union is an operation on sets that brings all elements of set <m>A</m> and all elements of set <m>B</m> together.
            i.e., <me>
              A \cup B = \{x : x \in A \text{ or } x \in B\}.
            </me>
            In mathematics, <alert>or</alert> means <term>either</term> or <term>both</term>.
          </p>
          <p>
            If <m>A =\{a, e, i, o, u\} </m> and <m>B=\{i, u \}</m>, then  <m>A \cup B = \{a, e, i, o, u\}</m>
            <term>Note: </term> if <m> B \subset A</m>, then <m>A \cup B = A.</m>
          </p>
          <p>
          <alert>Properties of Union:</alert> 
          </p> 
          <p>
          <ol marker ="i.">
            <li>
              <p>
                <m>A \cup B = B \cup A</m> (Commulative law)
              </p>
            </li>
            <li>
              <p>
                <m>(A \cup B) \cup C = A \cup (B \cup C)</m> (Associative law)
              </p>
            </li>
            <li>
              <p>
                <m>(A \cup \phi) = A</m> (Law of identity element)
              </p>
            </li>
            <li>
              <p>
                <m>(A \cup A) = A</m> (Indempotent Law)
              </p>
            </li>
            <li>
              <p>
                <m>(\bigcup \cup A) = \bigcup </m> (Law of Universal Set)
              </p>
            </li>
          </ol>
        </p>
        </li>
        <li>
          <p>
            <term>Intersection of Sets: </term> 
            Let <m>A =\{2, 4, 6, 8\} </m> and <m>B=\{6, 8, 10, 12 \}</m> be two arbitrary sets, 
            then intersection of <m>A</m> and <m>B</m> is written as 
            <me>
              A \cap B.
            </me>
            Where  <me>
              A \cap B = \{6, 8\}
            </me>
            Intersection is an operation on sets that brings common elements of set <m>A</m> and set <m>B</m> together.
            i.e., <me>
              A \cap B = \{x : x \in A \text{ and } x \in B\}.
            </me>
            In mathematics, <term>and</term> means <term>simultaneously</term>.
          </p>
          <p>
            If <m>A =\{a, e, i, o, u\} </m> and <m>B=\{i, u \}</m>, then  <m>A \cap B = \{i, u\}</m>
            <term>Note: </term> if <m> B \subset A</m>, then <m>A \cap B = B.</m>
          </p>
          <p>
          <alert>Properties of Intersection:</alert>
          <ol marker ="i.">
            <li>
              <p>
                <m>A \cap B = B \cap A</m> (Commulative law)
              </p>
            </li>
            <li>
              <p>
                <m>(A \cap B) \cap C = A \cap (B \cap C)</m> (Associative law)
              </p>
            </li>
            <li>
              <p>
                <m>(\phi \cap A) = \phi </m>, <m>\bigcup \cap A = A</m> (Law of <m>\phi </m> &amp; <m> \bigcup </m>)
              </p>
            </li>
            <li>
              <p>
                <m>(A \cap A) = A</m> (Indempotent Law)
              </p>
            </li>
            <li>
              <p>
                <m>A \cap (B \cup C) = (A \cap B) \cup (A \cap C) </m> (Distributive Law)
              </p>
            </li>
          </ol>
        </p>
        </li>
        <li>
          <p>
            <term>Difference of Sets:</term>
            Let <m>A =\{1, 2, 3, 4, 5, 6\} </m> and <m>B=\{2, 4, 6, 8 \}</m> be two arbitrary sets, 
            then difference of sets <m>A</m> and <m>B</m> is given as  
            <me>
              A - B = \{1, 3, 5\} 
            </me>
            and   <me>
              B - A = \{ 8\}
            </me>
            Therefore <m>A - B \neq B - A.</m>
          </p>
          <p>
            <me>
              A - B = \{x : x \in A \text{ but } x \not\in B.\} 
            </me>
          </p>
        </li>
        <li>
          <p>
            <term>Complement of a Set:</term> 
            It is the set of all elements in the universal set, <m>\cup</m> that are not in set, <m>A</m>. 
            It is denoted by <m>A'</m> or <m>A^C</m>.
             <me>
              A' = \{x : x \in \cup \text{ and } x \not\in A\}
             </me>
             
             Alternatively, complement of a set is the difference of the universal set, <m>\cup</m> and 
             the subset, <m>A</m>. i.e., 
             <me>
              A' = \cup - A.
             </me>
             
                      </p>
                      <p>
                        Suppose, the universal set  <m>\cup = \{ x: x \in \mathbb W \text{ and } 1 \leq x \leq 9 \}</m>.
                          If  <m>A=\{1,2,4\}</m>, then <m>A^c=\{3,5,6,7,8,9\}</m>.
                      </p>
        </li>
      </ol>
    </p>
  </introduction>
 

  <subsection xml:id="subsec-DeMorgn">
    <title>De Morgan's Law in Set Theory</title>
    <p>
      De Morgan's law defines the relationship between the union, intersection, and complements of the sets. 
      In set theory, there are two De Morgan's Laws:
         </p>
         <p>
          <term>First De Morgan's Law</term> The complement of the union of two sets is equal to the intersection 
          of the complements of each set. That is,
            <me>
              (A \cup B)' = A' \cap B'
            </me>
             </p>
         <p>
          <term>Second De Morgan's Law</term> The complement of intersection of two sets is equal to the 
          union of the complements of each set.
          That is, 
          <me>
            (A \cap B)' = A' \cup B'
          </me>
         </p>
  </subsection>
  


</section>